{{Use Australian English|date=April 2014}}
'''Gillon McLachlan'''  (born 1973)<ref name=who/> is the Chief Executive Officer of the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). He was appointed Chief Executive Officer of the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL) on 30 April 2014, succeeding [[Andrew Demetriou]]. He had previously been his deputy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gillon McLachlan announced as new AFL CEO|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/live-gillon-mclachlan-announced-as-new-afl-ceo-20140430-37gqm.html|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=The Age|date=30 April 2014}}</ref>

==Personal==
McLachlan grew up on his family farm 'Rosebank', located in [[Mount Pleasant, South Australia]]. His parents are [[Angus McLachlan|Angus]], a former first class cricketer, and Sylvia.<ref name=who/><ref name=lane>{{cite news|last=Lane|first=Sam|title=The man who will be king of the AFL|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/the-man-who-will-be-king-of-the-afl-20140430-zr235.html|accessdate=1 May 2014|newspaper=The Age|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> He is the eldest of four brothers: [[Hamish McLachlan|Hamish]], Will and Banjo.<ref name=who>{{cite news|title=What you need to know about the AFLâ€™s new boss, Gillon McLachlan|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-afls-new-boss-gillon-mclachlan/story-fndv7pj3-1226900572853|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=News.com|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> His uncle, [[Ian McLachlan]], was an [[Australian government]] [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]], and was long term President (up to 2014) of the [[South Australian Cricket Association]].

After completing secondary school as a boarder at [[St Peter's College, Adelaide]],<ref name=who/> he obtained a [[Bachelor of Commerce]] at the [[University of Adelaide]] in 1995 and a [[Bachelor of Laws]] (Honours) at the [[University of Melbourne]] in 1996, where he was a resident at [[Trinity College (University of Melbourne)|Trinity College]]. He later completed the Senior Executive Program at [[Stanford University]].<ref name=who/> He is married to Laura Blythe, who was a fellow resident at Trinity College and is the daughter of former [[Spotless (Australian business)|Spotless]] Chairman, Brian Blythe.<ref name=who/> The McLachlans have four children: Edie, Cleo, Sidney and Luna.<ref name=who/><ref name=lane/>

==Sports career==
McLachlan played [[Australian football]] in the [[Hills Football League]] colts competition for the now defunct Pleasant Valley club. After moving to Melbourne, he played with [[Melbourne University Football Club|Melbourne University Blues]] in the [[Victorian Amateur Football Association]] (VAFA).<ref name=who/> Besides playing as a ruckman for the club (1994-2003), he was captain (2000-2002), C.W. McLeod Trophy for best-and-fairest (2000),<ref>{{cite web |title=Honour Board |url=http://www.uniblues.com/about-uni-blues/honour-board/ |work=Uniblues F.C. website |accessdate=1 May 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526064440/http://www.uniblues.com/about-uni-blues/honour-board/ |archivedate=26 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>  committeeman and made a life member (2003).<ref name=who/><ref>{{cite web|title=Earlier today |url=http://www.uniblues.com/earlier-today/ |work=Uniblues FC website |accessdate=1 May 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002551/http://www.uniblues.com/earlier-today/ |archivedate=2 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> He was a regular VAFA Representative including captain.  He was on the [[Carlton Football Club]] supplementary list from 1996 to 1997. McLachlan has represented Victoria in [[polo]] and has been a national selector.<ref name=who/>

==Business career==
After leaving university, McLachlan worked as a management consultant with [[Accenture]].<ref name=who/> In 2000, he was employed as a strategy consultant to the AFL by CEO [[Wayne Jackson (footballer)|Wayne Jackson]].<ref name=who/> In 2003, he was appointed as General Manager of Commercial Operations and in 2008 was appointed Chief Operating Officer.<ref name=top50>{{cite news|title=Top 50 Sport 2013 - Gillon McLachlan|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/top50/2013/gillon-mclachlan/story-fnhacnov-1226587675071|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=The Australian}}</ref> In December 2012, he was appointed Deputy CEO.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gillon McLachlan earns promotion to AFL deputy CEO|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/gillon-mclachlan-earns-promotion-to-afl-deputy-ceo/story-fnelctok-1226540524846|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=News.com.au|date=19 December 2012}}</ref> Before taking on the CEO role at the AFL, McLachlan played a major role in delivering stadiums for two new teams - [[Gold Coast Suns]] and [[GWS Giants]], established the AFL media department and negotiated the media broadcast deal of $1.25 billion.<ref name=thesmh/><ref>{{cite news|last=Hinds|first=Richard|title=Little known about wanted man, but CV suggests code switch wouldn't be out of his league|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/little-known-about-wanted-man-but-cv-suggests-code-switch-wouldnt-be-out-of-his-league-20120829-251c6.html|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 August 2012}}</ref> In 2013, he supervised the AFL's investigation into the [[Melbourne Football Club tanking scandal]] and the negotiations with [[Essendon Football Club supplements controversy]].<ref name=thesmh>{{cite news|title=AFL names Gillon McLachlan as new CEO|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/afl-names-gillon-mclachlan-as-new-ceo-20140430-37gma.html|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=theabc>{{cite news|title=Gillon McLachlan to take over as AFL chief executive from Andrew Demetriou in June|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-30/gillon-mclachlan-named-afl-chief-executive/5420314|accessdate=30 April 2014|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> On 30 April 2014, the AFL Chairman [[Mike Fitzpatrick (footballer)|Mike Fitzpatrick]] announced McLachlan would be appointed as AFL CEO replacing [[Andrew Demetriou]].<ref name=ninemsn>{{cite news|last=Vaughan|first=Roger|title=New AFL boss moves to calm fans|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8837363|accessdate=30 April 2014|newspaper=Ninemsn|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> At the announcement of his appointment, McLachlan stated: ''I've been part of the community of football and I know how important it is. I played over 200 games of amateur or country football, I've captained a club, I've been on a committee of a club, I'm a life member of a club. I've had my share of cold showers and freezing committee meetings. I've been part of appointing coaches and sacking coaches. I have a clear vision of where the game needs to go and how we're going to get there. For me that vision is about having an unassailable hold on the Australian community.''<ref>{{cite web|title=Gillon McLachlan named AFL CEO|url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2014/04/30/gillon-mclachlan-named-afl-ceo-live-updates/|work=The Roar, 30 April 2014|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

In 2012, it was reported that he rejected the CEO positions at the [[National Rugby League]]<ref name=thesmh/> and [[Liverpool F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/afl/gillon-mclachlan-knocks-back-position-with-epl-giant-liverpool/story-e6frexx0-1226463132076 |title=Gillon McLachlan knocks back position with EPL giant Liverpool |last1=Stevens |first1=Mark |last2= |first2= |date=2 September 2012 |website=Daily Telegraph |publisher=News Ltd |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

In 2014, McLachlan was appointed Patron for the [[Children's Cancer Foundation (Australia)|Children's Cancer Foundation]]. McLachlan stated: "Australian football is built on community. We are only as strong as the community in which we reside. The Children's Cancer Foundation's values reflect the AFL's commitment to effecting positive social change." Since 2015, McLachlan has also been a member of The Million Dollar Lunch Committee. <ref>{{cite web|title=Our Patron|url=https://childrenscancerfoundation.com.au/about-us/our-patron|work=Children's Cancer Foundation website}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Million Dollar Lunch hits the mark|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/million-dollar-lunch-hits-the-mark-20141017-117pql.html|work=The Age, 17 October 2014}}</ref>

